Here's how to implement all three pieces:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");

                if (leave)
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            });

            return true; // cancel the default navigation
        }

        return false; // allow normal back
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/OS back button** (Android). It does *not* fire for Shell's navigation bar back arrow.

**3. Replace the Shell back arrow with a custom "Cancel" button**

Hide the default back button and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            IsVisible="True"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline (more common):

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

Then in your view model or code-behind:

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }

public EditProductPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();

    CancelCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });

    BindingContext = this;
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior` replaces the nav-bar back arrow — this is where your "Cancel" text and confirmation logic live.
- `OnBackButtonPressed` covers the Android/hardware back button separately.
- Both paths should share the same confirmation logic.
